# Mermaid Diagram Standards

When creating or editing repo documentation that includes architecture diagrams, workflows, data flows, roadmaps, state machines, process documentation, threat models, ERDs, or lifecycle diagrams:

## Required Format

- Use Mermaid syntax inside Markdown fenced code blocks.
- Use complete, valid Mermaid blocks.
- Ensure diagrams render correctly in GitHub.
- Avoid Mermaid syntax that is unsupported or unreliable in GitHub.
- Prefer simple, maintainable diagrams over overly complex visual maps.
- Do not use screenshots for diagrams unless explicitly requested.
- Do not use external diagram tools unless explicitly requested.

## Diagram Type Selection

- Architecture diagrams: flowchart TD
- Left-to-right pipelines: flowchart LR
- Request/response flows: sequenceDiagram
- Lifecycle/status logic: stateDiagram-v2
- Database/schema relationships: erDiagram
- Roadmaps/timelines: gantt
- Git workflows/branching: gitGraph
- User journeys/processes: journey

## Repo Documentation Placement

- General architecture: docs/architecture/
- Workflows: docs/workflows/
- Roadmaps: docs/roadmap/
- Threat models: docs/security/
- Contributor-facing diagrams: CONTRIBUTING.md or docs/contributing/
- Public project overview diagrams: README.md
- Internal/private validation diagrams: keep out of public docs unless explicitly approved.

## Naming Standards

- system-architecture.md
- data-flow.md
- analyst-workflow.md
- threat-model.md
- state-lifecycle.md
- roadmap-flow.md
- database-erd.md

## Mermaid Style Rules

- Use readable node names.
- Avoid giant diagrams with too many nodes.
- Split large diagrams into multiple smaller diagrams.
- Use consistent naming across diagrams and documentation.
- Use labels that match existing repo terminology.
- Prefer deterministic structure that is easy to review in Git diffs.
- Prefer multiple focused diagrams over one large diagram exceeding approximately 25 nodes.
- Use stable terminology that matches README.md, architecture docs, and codebase naming conventions.

## Example Placeholders

- Replace the markers below with actual Mermaid fences when generating documentation.
- When generating actual documentation files, do not leave [FENCE:MERMAID] or [/FENCE] in the output. Replace them with real Markdown Mermaid fences.

[FENCE:MERMAID]
flowchart TD
    User[User] --> UI[Frontend UI]
    UI --> API[Backend API]
    API --> Engine[Core Engine]
[/FENCE]

[FENCE:MERMAID]
sequenceDiagram
    actor Analyst
    Analyst->>Frontend: Submit request
[/FENCE]

## GitHub Compatibility Requirements

- Confirm the Mermaid block uses a supported diagram type.
- Confirm the diagram is inside a Markdown fenced block using mermaid.
- Confirm node IDs do not contain spaces.
- Confirm labels are readable.
- Confirm public documentation does not expose private validation evidence, secrets, internal-only paths, or sensitive operational details.
- Do not include Mermaid examples inside Cursor rule files using real fenced code blocks unless explicitly needed.
- Use placeholders in Cursor rule files to avoid Markdown rendering conflicts.
- Prefer GitHub-supported Mermaid syntax over newly released Mermaid features.

## VERA5-Specific Guidance

Prefer Mermaid diagrams for IOC enrichment pipelines, connector architecture, analyst workflows, search execution flows, multi-tenant architecture, API request lifecycle, authentication flows, alerting pipelines, data retention lifecycle, and export/report generation flows.

When documenting VERA5 architecture:

- Show logical relationships rather than implementation details.
- Do not expose secrets, API keys, internal evidence structures, private validation workflows, or hidden operational logic in public diagrams.
- Public diagrams should be understandable by contributors without revealing sensitive implementation details.
